<subSubSection id="E76DE507C7E1840677F133E751FE067B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="41BEACCC3396E5A4051F9BAFDEF641B7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="02F0E8EA3C7F40440020C03E992C0219" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="70FF4A5447B0C5ACDA08987529AAEC35" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oranensis">
<emphasis id="B9C1820A38A6E2BEE96E1C4F4B87C7B8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea oranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but immediately distinguished by the hypocratiform corolla with a cylindrical tube and exserted genitalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D0862B92C735A9FC0EDE1A646004ACF8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Both 
<taxonomicName id="D893D7CD8A08DFF3F340D52E7C5039B7" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="exserta">
<emphasis id="D24B43E50575D0F6A75327D424B2EA8D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea exserta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D2C7657DD3D360E6243827D44923EB32" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oranensis">
<emphasis id="0B1D704C5BCF1A6C7355B02482AAA075" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. oranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have some stellate hairs mixed with unbranched hairs but these are often difficult to see. The two species may sometimes grow together but 
<taxonomicName id="57E7FE4D8B58FCEE634D903E74756799" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oranensis">
<emphasis id="A4BECF63210DEF08AC5467B0CED937D9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. oranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found most commonly at higher altitudes, from 1600 to 2200 m, although there are a few records from as low as 650 m.
</paragraph>
